ce:section.ce:para:
CDs have been prepared from virtually any carbon-containing precursor, such as citrates and amines [72,103–105], phenylenediamines [106], polymers [107], graphite [85], carbon soot [108], ionic liquid [80], saccharides [109], biomass [11,110], cigarette smoke [100], chicken blood [101], human hair [111], human urine [102], and whatnot. Reportedly, endogenous CDs have been found in food items [112], soft and alcoholic drinks [113,114], and human blood [115], also. Though, there are two basic approaches in pyrolysis of small organic molecules (bottom-up) and break-down of large carbonaceous materials (top-down); over the years we have witnessed nearly a dozen synthesis routes that have been exercised for this job (Table 2
                     , Fig. 2
                     ). CDs synthesized through bottom-up approaches possess assorted surface functionalities, great flexibility, and tunability, which are otherwise impossible to achieve through top-down synthesis. On the other hand, top-down approaches do not enjoy the luxury of raw materials to choose from and hence are free from the bafflement that arises from over-abundancy.
